1.

I have said here before that I am generally not a fan of writing about writing. Generally, when I stumble on a new writer who is preoccupied with the demimonde of other writers, with writing as a mÃ©tier, a lifestyle, a praxis, etc., I am confident in judging right away that this person has almost certainly never tried their hand at writing about quasars. On the other hand, there is a venerable pedigree to the idea that the human condition is a disorder, if not of course one understood in the crudely medicalized terms of the DSM. It is also idolatry: making as if the things of the world itself were even in principle capable of providing the happiness that in fact can only come from You Know Who (the ultimate adjudicator of what is horse-pucky and what is not).

And yet, remarkably, Augustine finds a way, after his conversion, to keep writing anyway. Could one discern in his Confessions, I have been asking myself recently, a model of how to write without all this writing coming down to the ridiculous and infantile plea: Look at me?

At times I have supposed that the best way to avoid suggesting such a reductive translation is to keep the writing focused on quasars and nudibranchs, and other such things as Aristotle recognized to be, in their own way, divine (â€œHere too dwell gods,â€ he declared when knee-deep in the tide pool, citing Heraclitus, fondling a starfish). Augustine seems to have had a similar realization, if we replace malacology in the example with the totality of classical pagan learning. St. Augustine for his part dwells on everything he has learned, appeals to some of the more useful insights of the pre-Christian Greeks, but always comes back to the view that all of this is nothing, but nothing, in the absence of faith in Jesus Christ, the Son of God.

I generally find that Augustine is far too hard on himself. It seems to me that there is an insurmountable tension and a real ambiguity in any interest we might take in the world, such that this interest must always threaten to cross over into idolatry and forgetfulness. But it also seems to me, at the same time, that one must risk crossing over in this way in order to delight in the wonder of creation, which is surely a good thing, and which even Augustine seems to think God would want us to do. He is honest enough to recognize more generally that the line between sin and virtue is difficult at times to discern â€” so that, for example, whether saving up money is admirable frugality or rather deplorable avarice may be something we are not in a position definitively to decide. Part of what it is to be a creature born of sin, he thinks, is to be objectively unable to know when exactly you are sinning.

It seems to me that our attention to the things of the world is necessarily characterized by the same sort of uncertainty. I myself have always been prone to idolatry â€” to loving quasars and nudibranchs and all the forms and qualities the world throws forth for us. For this reason, those Christian authors tend to elicit greater sympathy in me who understand attention to nature as already a sort of worship, either because they are deviant in their time, like St. Francis of Assisi or St. Theodora of Sihla, or because they have one foot outside of the millennia-long faith to which they are still nominally attached, and so speak to us in vague terms about a properly Christian comportment to nature, when what they really want to do is get right down to the comporting â€” here I would mention Goethe, or Emerson.

I love the Jesuits, too, who, from the time of Matteo Ricciâ€™s arrival in China to the recent Sanskrit scholarship of Francis X. I love grammar â€” English, Latin, Sanskrit, Sakha, whatever. Sometimes I go to the theater and watch people pretend to die. I like these characters because theyâ€™re wrong, because theyâ€™re clueless. You should be like Jesus and hang with the thieves and prostitutes; but presumably you should join them with at least some reserve, and not go so far as to adopt their life-ways; yet this half in-half out approach is a pretty surefire way of making the thieves and prostitutes resent you in your aloofness.

When I have had enough of Augustine and Emerson, I have been going back, again, to Heidegger, and trying to see what I may have missed on my last reading of Being and Time years ago. Augustine wishes to reject pagan learning for Christian truth, which to him is the same as rejecting death in favor of life; Emerson wishes to reject the hegemony of European taste-making and the authority of dusty antiquarian book-learning, in favor of a spontaneous sort of thinking that is fit for the new era, which is to say the burgeoning era of American dominance; Heidegger wishes to â€œovercome metaphysicsâ€, which is to say the accrued weight of our inherited philosophical traditions, in order to recover the thinking of Being that had been occluded by the lesser question of the nature of beings, and thereby to retrieve some kind of primordial condition that he associates with authenticity.

I find that I can only really sympathize with one of these authors. I have already explained my difficulty in accompanying Augustine all the way: I am not prepared to repent of my love of grammar, tragedy, nature, etc.

But Emerson! Emerson said some things that had never been said before, and practically brought America into being by language alone. I take the existence of America to be neither good nor bad, but still a brute fact of the world that, in my own case at least, must be confronted as a significant component of the project of self-knowledge. The world Emerson is prophesying into existence, and in particular its discontinuity with the Old World, is the world I know best, and the one I took for granted for far too long. It is a world of curiosity and dilettantism, autodidactic dispersion, not much left in the way of sincere fear of God, and a lot of hustling and hucksterism pursued under the name of religion, yet whose ultimate translation always turns out to be: Look at me.

Augustine and Emerson are both driven by the same core belief that, properly seen, every person turns out to be infinite. What we have to do to access this infinity is very different in each case â€” to accept that the life of this world is in fact death, for Augustine; for Emerson it can be enough to take a walk and to be reminded of â€œthe occult relation between man and the vegetableâ€, even if ultimately it is Christianity that best understands and centers â€œmanâ€™s infinityâ€. How now does Dasein tap into its infinity? It does not seem that Heidegger has any such expectation of a life re-geared for authenticity. This is why so many of the children of the twentieth century, myself surely included, have had recourse to irony as our primary mode of engagement with the world, which enables us to make due with the ordinary cultural objects that fill up modern life, but smirkingly to twist our experience of them in a way that mimics transcendence â€” not â€œGod is greatâ€, and not â€œNature is sublimeâ€, but â€œLee Hazlewood is cool, and I should like his likeness on a t-shirtâ€. In my experience only idiots make use of the facile clichÃ© about intellectual work being a sort of â€œmental masturbationâ€. But just as attitudes towards masturbation can change, so can the cultural position and moral valence of writing migrate from one century to the next. If writing is like masturbation, it seems to me, this is not masturbation in an era of dangerous population bottlenecking, where indeed there is good reason to avoid â€œwasting seedâ€, but rather something more like masturbation in an era in which reproduction has in any case been entirely transferred to the management of biotechnology companies, sex has been outlawed, and any return in our private time to our vestigial anatomy and its potencies can only leave us with a sense of melancholy for all that has been lost, and of the exceeding smallness of the small pleasure we are still permitted.

Iâ€™ve been making variations on this point for some time now. Look at what is happening to material culture more generally â€” a domain no less semiotically laden than writing, even if it takes at least some different skills to read the signs. In 1980 I recall seeing a Snoopy-themed kitchen mixer on the counter in a friendâ€™s home. This did not surprise me; it made sense that there should be such a thing. If you had asked me in 1980 whether there is also, say, a Batman-themed vacuum cleaner somewhere out there in the world, my intuition would have been that there is not. By 2000, I would no longer be so sure. By 2020, I think I would affirm with a high degree of confidence that there probably is a Batman-themed vacuum cleaner somewhere. By 2020 there was also, probably, a pair of Terminator 2-themed roller skates, somewhere, a Better Call Saul Trapper notebook, and so on. By the time the pandemic hit, it was almost as if simply being able to think of some cultural artifact was enough for it to have its being, just like the classical conception of the Divine Imagination, where the simple idea of something is already a willing of it into being.

One way of thinking about cultural artifacts in the era of automated overproduction is that this is the moment in the history of technology when possibility and actuality become coextensive. Even if a special order may have to be put in, so that some fly-by-night Amazon partner can move into production and send you the custom t-shirts you have requested featuring, say, Patti LaBelle riding a centaur, every conceivable commercial product now remains at every moment â€œas good as doneâ€. What is more, I believe we have begun to witness a process of recursion, in which things are about to get a lot more intricate, and cultural objects a lot harder to decipher. By 2030 I expect it will be reasonable to suppose, without even looking into the matter, not only that there are Terminator 2-themed roller skates, but also that there are Batman-vacuum-cleaner-themed Terminator 2-themed roller skates, say, where instead of a leather jacket the Schwarzenegger character is depicted on the skates as wearing a garment with a Batman-vacuum-cleaner motif. Perhaps by 2040 or so we will start to see Batman-vacuum-cleaner-themed-Terminator 2-roller-skate-themed vacuum cleaners. And so on.

It will be difficult for us human beings, at a certain level of recursive complexity, even to envision what such artifacts will look like. But our own imaginative limitations are of no concern for the AI that will be churning out all this garbage. Eventually, we may suppose that the thematic recursion of the artifacts will display the properties of fractals, and as these keep subdividing they will become, if there are any spectators left to watch, indistinguishable from what is called â€œgrey gooâ€, a sort of nanotechnological alkahest that replicates itself by devouring ever more of the world around it, until nothing at all is left other than the goo. That the goo may also feature, at a microscopic level, the tiny likenesses of Snoopy, Patti LaBelle, Arnold Schwarzenegger, and the rest of the gang that has kept us such close company in the final years of this pivotal era, may be a minor fact about the apocalypse, but likely a curious one to any extraterrestrial who may show up later to inspect the ruins.

Perhaps I am exaggerating somewhat â€”things will probably be just fineâ€”, but I think I can be forgiven for imagining doomsday scenarios that involve such cultural detritus as I have invited you to picture. It feels as if we are being buried alive, and much the same feeling cannot fail to accompany our recent encounters with the written word.

We have all likely seen variations on the chart showing the explosion of big data in recent years: the total data volume worldwide in 2023, at 120 zettabytes, is roughly sixty times greater than it was as recently as 2010. Any chart fine-grained enough to show the two zettabytes of 2010 as a measurable quantity, will also show any year before 2000 or so as basically a flatline running along the bottom of the chart. And that flatline extends throughout the entire history of literacy, from ancient Chinese oracle bones to Y2K. Under such circumstances, it is hard for anyone to make any real sense of what we are doing when we are writing, and it is damned hard to keep away the suspicion that we are only indulging an ingrained compulsion that has outlived its era of historical meaningfulness. The appropriate feeling in response to this suspicion is one of melancholy and loss, and perhaps a bit of shame at the lack of vision and fortitude that keeps us going back to the old habits, the old anatomy of life, even when they have been superseded by greater technologies, rather than working to envision a new sense of the human, to discover human capacities that could not even in principle be threatened by these technologies.

What are these capacities? I donâ€™t know; thatâ€™s why I keep writing.

3.

I have always been a maximalist. I can recall a Halloween parade at my Catholic elementary school, fifth grade or so. My costume was a composite of all possible costumes. A year or so later there was another event at school, one designed to teach us something about the behavior of bodies under the laws of classical mechanics.
